[
  {
    "topic": "Node.js Tutorial",
    "lessons": [
      {
        "title": "Node HOME",
        "fileName": "default.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/default.asp.html",
        "summary": "This introductory lesson defines Node.js as an open-source runtime for executing JavaScript outside the browser. It explores the platform's non-blocking architecture, ideal for building scalable servers and real-time apps. Students learn to use built-in modules, manage packages via npm, and run scripts through the terminal."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Intro",
        "fileName": "nodejs_intro.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_intro.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson introduces Node.js as a high-performance, asynchronous JavaScript runtime for server-side development. It covers core concepts like the event loop, non-blocking I/O, and building scalable web servers or APIs. Students will explore file management, database interaction, and deployment."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Get Started",
        "fileName": "nodejs_get_started.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_get_started.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson covers the installation of Node.js and how to verify it using the command line interface. Students learn to create a simple web server with the built-in http module and execute their first script. By the end, you will be able to run a local server and display \"Hello World\" in a browser."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node JS Requirements",
        "fileName": "nodejs_js_requirements.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_js_requirements.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson covers essential JavaScript prerequisites for Node.js, such as variables, ES6+ features, and objects. It focuses on asynchronous programming through promises and async/await to prepare learners for server-side logic. These fundamentals provide a vital foundation for building modern applications."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node.js vs Browser",
        "fileName": "nodejs_vs_browser.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_vs_browser.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson explores the fundamental differences between Node.js and browser environments, focusing on their respective server-side and client-side roles. While both execute JavaScript, they vary in API availability, global objects, module systems, and security levels. Understanding these distinctions is vital for developing efficient full-stack applications."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Cmd Line",
        "fileName": "nodejs_command_line.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_command_line.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson covers fundamental Node.js command-line operations, including script execution, REPL usage, and argument handling. Students learn to configure environment variables, debug applications with inspector flags, and utilize essential tools like npm for effective project management."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node V8 Engine",
        "fileName": "nodejs_v8_engine.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_v8_engine.asp.html",
        "summary": "V8 is Google’s open-source engine that compiles JavaScript into native machine code for high-speed execution in Node.js. It leverages JIT compilation and efficient memory management to optimize performance. As the core runtime, V8 provides the essential environment for modern, server-side JavaScript."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Architecture",
        "fileName": "nodejs_architecture.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_architecture.asp.html",
        "summary": "Node.js employs a single-threaded, event-driven architecture that leverages a non-blocking I/O model and an event loop. By offloading heavy tasks to a thread pool, it efficiently handles thousands of concurrent connections. This makes it a powerful choice for scalable APIs and real-time apps."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Event Loop",
        "fileName": "nodejs_event_loop.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_event_loop.asp.html",
        "summary": "The Node.js event loop is a single-threaded mechanism that enables non-blocking asynchronous operations and high concurrency. It processes tasks in specific phases, prioritizing synchronous code and microtasks before timers and I/O. This architecture is essential for building scalable real-time applications."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "topic": "Asynchronous",
    "lessons": [
      {
        "title": "Node Async",
        "fileName": "nodejs_async.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_async.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson explores non-blocking I/O in Node.js, focusing on the transition from callbacks to Promises and async/await. It highlights performance benefits and provides best practices for error handling and parallel execution. Students learn to write clean, scalable code while avoiding callback hell."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Promises",
        "fileName": "nodejs_promises.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_promises.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson introduces Node.js Promises as a clean alternative to callbacks for managing asynchronous operations. It covers promise states, chaining, and error handling via .then() and .catch(). Students will also master static methods like Promise.all() to handle multiple operations in parallel."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Async/Await",
        "fileName": "nodejs_async_await.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_async_await.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson introduces async/await in Node.js as a modern, readable way to handle asynchronous operations. It covers core syntax, try/catch error handling, and parallel execution using Promise.all. Students learn to write cleaner, maintainable code by following industry best practices."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Errors Handling",
        "fileName": "nodejs_error_handling.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_error_handling.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson explores essential strategies for managing errors in Node.js to ensure application stability. It covers common error types, traditional callback patterns, modern async/await handling, and global exception management. Students learn to implement robust practices for debugging and resource cleanup."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "topic": "Module Basics",
    "lessons": [
      {
        "title": "Node Modules",
        "fileName": "nodejs_modules.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_modules.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson explores Node.js modules as essential tools for code organization and reusability. It details the CommonJS system, covering built-in modules, custom exports, and the require function. Students also learn about module resolution, caching, and best practices for building scalable applications."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node ES Modules",
        "fileName": "nodejs_modules_esm.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_modules_esm.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson explores Node.js ES Modules (ESM), highlighting differences from CommonJS like static imports and top-level await. It covers enabling ESM via file extensions or package.json settings. Developers learn syntax for named, default, and dynamic exports to build modern applications."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node NPM",
        "fileName": "nodejs_npm.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_npm.asp.html",
        "summary": "NPM is the primary package manager for Node.js, allowing developers to download and manage modular JavaScript libraries. This lesson explains how to install packages locally or globally, integrate them into code, and perform essential maintenance like updating or uninstalling external dependencies."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node package.json",
        "fileName": "nodejs_package_json.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_package_json.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson explores package.json, the essential manifest file for any Node.js project. It covers creation via npm init, metadata configuration, and dependency management. Students also learn to define custom scripts and apply versioning best practices to ensure project stability and security."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node NPM Scripts",
        "fileName": "nodejs_scripts.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_scripts.asp.html",
        "summary": "NPM scripts allow developers to automate common project tasks like running, testing, and building applications. These commands are defined within the \"scripts\" section of the package.json file. You can execute them using the \"npm run\" command, while specialized scripts like start and test offer shorthand alternatives."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Manage Dep",
        "fileName": "nodejs_dependencies.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_dependencies.asp.html",
        "summary": "This lesson covers Node.js dependency management using tools like npm and Yarn. It explains semantic versioning, package installation types, and the role of lock files in maintaining consistency. Students also learn to update and audit dependencies to ensure project security and long-term stability."
      },
      {
        "title": "Node Publish Packages",
        "fileName": "nodejs_publish_package.asp.md",
        "url": "https://www.w3schools.com/nodejs/nodejs_publish_package.asp.html"
      }
    ]
  },
